The reason your cluster is still down is now very precise and clear:


---

🚨 Problem in your registries.conf

Right now you have:

location = "quay.io/openshift-release-dev/ocp-release"

[[registry.mirror]]
location = "bastion-sno.lab.ocp.lan:8443/ocp4/openshift4"

👉 But your mirror (from oc-mirror) actually lives at:

bastion-sno.lab.ocp.lan:8443/ocp4/openshift4/openshift-release-dev/ocp-release


---

❌ Why this breaks things

Node tries:

quay.io/openshift-release-dev/ocp-release
→ mirror → bastion/.../ocp4/openshift4

👉 But image is actually deeper:

.../ocp4/openshift4/openshift-release-dev/ocp-release

➡️ So CRI-O cannot find it → kubelet stays down


---

✅ Correct fix (VERY IMPORTANT)

Edit your file:

vi /etc/containers/registries.conf


---

🔥 Replace ONLY the first block with this:

[[registry]]
  prefix = ""
  location = "quay.io/openshift-release-dev"

  [[registry.mirror]]
    location = "bastion-sno.lab.ocp.lan:8443/ocp4/openshift4/openshift-release-dev"
    pull-from-mirror = "digest-only"


---

❗ REMOVE this incorrect part:

location = "quay.io/openshift-release-dev/ocp-release"


---

🧠 Why this works

Now mapping becomes:

quay.io/openshift-release-dev
→ bastion/.../openshift-release-dev

So:

ocp-release → resolves correctly ✅


---

🔥 Keep this in mind

oc-mirror → nested repo structure

so you MUST map at parent level, not full image path



---

✅ After fixing

Test redirect (VERY IMPORTANT)

podman pull quay.io/openshift-release-dev/ocp-release:4.14.46-x86_64

👉 It should pull from your mirror automatically


